<subsection xml:id="C31.S16.SS2">
<title>Heun Polynomial Products</title>        
  
 
<para xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p1">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="4" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p1.s1">
Expansions of Heun polynomial products in terms of Jacobi polynomial (§18.3)products are derived inKalnins and Miller (1991a, b, 1993) from the viewpoint of interrelation between two bases in a Hilbert space: <Math equation-number="31.16.1" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E1">\mathit{Hp}_{n,m}\left(x\right)\mathit{Hp}_{n,m}\left(y\right)=\sum_{j=0}^{n}A _{j}{\sin^{2j}}\theta\*P_{n-j}^{(\gamma+\delta+2j-1,\epsilon-1)}(\cos 2\theta) P_{j}^{(\delta-1,\gamma-1)}(\cos 2\phi),</Math> where <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p1.m1">n=0,1,\dots</Math> , <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p1.m2">m=0,1,\dots,n</Math> , and <Math equation-number="31.16.2" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E2">x={\sin^{2}}\theta{\cos^{2}}\phi,y={\sin^{2}}\theta{\sin^{2}}\phi</Math>.
</sentence>

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="2" sentence-num-in-section="5" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p1.s2">
The coefficients <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p1.m3">A_{j}</Math> satisfy the relations: <Math equation-number="31.16.3" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E3">Q_{0}A_{0}+R_{0}A_{1}=0,</Math> <Math equation-number="31.16.4" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E4">P_{j}A_{j-1}+Q_{j}A_{j}+R_{j}A_{j+1}=0, if j=1,2,\dots,n,</Math> where
</sentence>

</para>
  
<para xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p2">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="6" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p2.s1">
 <Math equation-number="31.16.5" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E5">P_{j}=\frac{(\epsilon-j+n)j(\beta+j-1)(\gamma+\delta+j-2)}{(\gamma+\delta+2j-3 )(\gamma+\delta+2j-2)},</Math> , <Math equation-number="31.16.6" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E6">Q_{j}=-aj(j+\gamma+\delta-1)-q+\frac{(j-n)(j+\beta)(j+\gamma)(j+\gamma+\delta- 1)}{(2j+\gamma+\delta)(2j+\gamma+\delta-1)}+\frac{(j+n+\gamma+\delta-1)j(j+ \delta-1)(j-\beta+\gamma+\delta-1)}{(2j+\gamma+\delta-1)(2j+\gamma+\delta-2)},</Math> , <Math equation-number="31.16.7" mode="display" xml:id="C31.S16.E7">R_{j}=\frac{(n-j)(j+n+\gamma+\delta)(j+\gamma)(j+\delta)}{(\gamma+\delta+2j)( \gamma+\delta+2j+1)}</Math>.
</sentence>

</para>
  
<para xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p3">

<sentence sentence-num-in-para="1" sentence-num-in-section="7" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p3.s1">
By specifying either <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p3.m1">\theta</Math> or <Math mode="inline" xml:id="C31.S16.SS2.p3.m2">\phi</Math> in (31.16.1) and (31.16.2) we obtain expansions in terms of one variable.
</sentence>

</para>
 
